text: One of the things, as the years passed, since I returned in 1970, I think one of the interesting things is that I'm okay with the defeat that America went through in Vietnam because I know it was the politicians who lost the war, not the military. And I think that's one of the things that frustrates me more today is the fact that it's like they don't want, our elected officials don't want us to win for a variety of reasons, and that's another show in itself. But the one good thing I'm proud of is the American society is absolutely reaching out to veterans. You have the Wounded Warrior Projects, you have TAPS, and I'll touch on that in a minute, but I see people going up to veterans who are wearing their decorations or a hat and they're thanking them for their service. My five-year-old granddaughter and I, our family, were at a granddaughter high school graduation on Thursday, and there was a Marine there. My five-year-old got so excited and reached out to him and said, thank you for your service. And, you know, those are the type of things that give me faith in the future. But, you know, when you think about that, you see, you turn on the news and you see the ISIS in the Middle East and the headlines are, you know, we don't have a plan to address it. And it seems that our president and our Congress, you know, they're willing to send these young men and women who aren't volunteers. They'll send them in harm's way and they don't have a plan to win. They just, they don't, there's not, I don't see, you know, in World War II, like the gentleman was saying, you didn't come home until it's over. And they knew what they had to do. They knew who the evil was and they knew, and yet they became the best equipped fighting force in the history of the world. But today, I am absolutely, afraid of the futures of my children and my grandchildren. And I'm doing everything in my power to make sure they understand that sacrifices are going to have to be made. And if they're not already in America, they're on their way. And our life, when I saw the towers fell, the first thing that went through my head was, it's the impact this is going to have on my grandkids that's going to be so important. Now, about my experience in Vietnam, I came from central Illinois, went to a school, 500 in our senior class. There were, it was, we had black students and white students, but I didn't have any black friends that I could call friends. And when I got there to Vietnam and I got to my outfit, I met a guy named Cleveland Ford. And I, it turned out that he was my first black friend and he was killed. And I met him. And I met with his folks who lived in Chicago years later. And I found out through pictures and super eight movies and letters he had sent home that I was his first white friend. And those are the type of things that I found in any type of a war zone. If you are in harm's way and you need help, you don't care if that hand that comes out as a white hand, a black hand, brown hand, whatever it is. And that's, that's the brotherhood. And that's the real thing. The real thing that pulls veterans together is the fact that if I need help, I know somebody's going to be there to help me. We've seen accidents on the highway and, and people just drive by them. I mean, but it's different, obviously. When I came home from Vietnam, my younger brother, Steve, he went to, he went to Vietnam in 1969 and he was a door gunner on a Huey helicopter that crashed and burned. And I was actually in Fort Sill, Oklahoma. And I found out through my TAC officer that he had died. And when I, I, I took my, I had a new son. I took my wife and we drove back to Decatur, Illinois. And the casualty officer did not know that I was still active duty military. And so he came over and he said, would you like to be the body escort for your brother? And my mother came over and put her arm around me and said, yes, he does. And there's an absolute, the best movie I have seen in many, many years called Taking Chance. It's a, it's a HBO documentary or a movie, HBO movie about a true story about a Marine officer who volunteers to escort a body home. And that's exactly what I did. I went out to San Francisco. I went through a day's training. I accepted the body. I got the airport, brought him back home, took him to the, took him to the funeral home. And we decided to have a, the funeral director and I decided it would be best to have a closed casket. And it was one of those things that my mother, to the day she died, she wasn't sure that her son was in there. But, you know, as I came back, I was treated with such honor, such, such respect. But the absolute hardest thing I ever did in my life is because I was the body escort, I was representing the president and America and the honor guard folded the flag. I saluted it. They handed it to me. They saluted it. And then I had to hand it to my mother. And that just was something that I had to do. And I did. I met yesterday with a Vietnam veteran. I met at the Wings over the Rockies Museum. We had a veteran's breakfast earlier this year. And, and we became, instant friends. And we went out to lunch this week and he had signed a confidential agreement. He, there was stuff he couldn't talk about for 40 years. No, time had expired. And I sit and listen to a man pour out his heart for three and a half hours. And it was my day to listen. There are stories that veterans have. You can't, they'll tell you if, if they want to. And this gentleman wanted to. And now I know I have a lifetime friend. Part of what I said earlier was TAPS. TAPS is not Wounded Warriors. They're still alive. TAPS is the Tragedy Assistance Program for Survivors. And it's for the families of our soldiers killed. Even those, and I heard this on your show earlier in a commercial, even those that commit suicide, we take care of their families, their kids, their spouses. It's an absolute wonderful charity. It's been 10 years in Colorado. We've raised several million dollars. It's the highest national rating of any charity where the, the amount of funds that end up assisting the benefits, the benefits, the family for the soldier killed is number one in the nation. We'll have a cash bar, hot dogs and hamburgers are also going to be there. But we raise money. And also we're having our annual TAPS thing that's going to be on Friday, June 26th. You can go to taps.org slash events and do that. And the last thing I'd like to share with you is that my wife and I and Bo and Lynn Cuttrell, we are stewards of a memorial. We had a young lady raise enough funds for us recently at a birthday party of all places that is going to allow us to take it to schools all over Colorado.
